abstract="Object-Based Image Analysis (OBIA) has gained considerable impetus over the last decade. However, despite the many newly developed methods and the numerous successful case studies, little effort has been directed towards building the conceptual foundations underlying it. In particular, there are at least two questions that need a clear answer before OBIA can be considered a discipline: i) What is the definition and ontological status of both image objects and geographic objects? And ii) How do they relate to each other? This chapter provides the authors' tentative response to these questions.",
